You are setting a variable to a value, then setting it again to null and trying to use the null value in an API that does not accept null values.

You write this:

    AgeSpinner = new Spinner&lt;&gt;();
    AgeSpinner = setValueFactory(new SpinnerValueFactory.IntegerSpinnerValueFactory(1, 100, 1));

And:

    private Spinner&lt;Double&gt; setValueFactory(DoubleSpinnerValueFactory doubleSpinnerValueFactory) {
        // TODO Auto-generated method stub
        return null;
    }

So you are setting the AgeSpinner to a value, then you are immediately setting it to null.

You then attempt to add the spinner to a GridPane:

    RegisterGP.add(AgeSpinner, 1, 1);

But the AgeSpinner is null and the GridPane throws an exception because it doesn&#39;t make sense to put a null value in a GridPane.

**Study Recommendations**

 * https://stackoverflow.com/questions/218384/what-is-a-nullpointerexception-and-how-do-i-fix-it
 * https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3988788/what-is-a-stack-trace-and-how-can-i-use-it-to-debug-my-application-errors
 * Microsoft&#39;s tutorial on [how to debug code](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/visualstudio/debugger/debugging-absolute-beginners?view=vs-2022&amp;tabs=csharp),
   - The Microsoft tutorial uses Visual Studio Code and C# or Visual Basic, so I don&#39;t advise following it directly (as it is not Java), but the article contains good info on how to debug.
