What you are describing is more of a rotate than a shift. Here is one way.  It is very simple and allows for left and right rotations.  A `negative` count rotates counter clockwise or to the `left`, a `positive` count clock wise or towards the `right`.

- First, ensure the array can be or needs to be rotated.  The rotation of an array of one element doesn&#39;t alter the array.  Nor does a rotation of `0` or the `length` of the array or any multiple of the length of the array.
- A negative rotation count is adjusted to an equivalent positive one.
  - count is always adjusted to `count%len`
  - then count is negated to conform to rotational directions.
  - if count is negative, it is adjusted to `len + count` 

Once the values are adjusted, a temp array of length count is created.

- the first `count` values are copied into this array.
- the the original array is shifted left `count` values.
- then the temp array added into the array in proper order.

```
 public static void rotate(Object[] array, int count) {
     int len = array.length;
     if (len &lt; 2 || count%len == 0) {
         return; // no rotation needed
     }
     count %= len;

     count = -count; // done to satisfy left and right direction
     if(count &lt; 0) {
         count = len + count;
     }

     Object[] temp = new Object[count];
     
     for (int i = 0; i &lt; count; i++) {
         temp[i] = array[i];
     }

     for (int i = count; i &lt; len; i++) {
         array[i - count] = array[i];
     }

     for (int k = 0, i = len - count; i &lt; len; i++) {
         array[i] = temp[k++];
     }
 }
```
To print you can do this.   Presumes `arrays` is `new someType[][] arrays ...`
```
for (Object[] obj : arrays) {
      System.out.println(Arrays.toString(obj));
}
```
One final note.  Using an Object array (e.g. `Object[]`) will not allow you to rotate primitive arrays(e.g. `int, long, double`, etc).  You will need a separate rotate method for each primitive type.

